	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Poe Responds to Spell Questions</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=447730" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <blockquote>
<p>Taken from the Everquest Official Forums:</p>

<p>xole wrote:</p>

<p>Here is a possible way to implement critical hits on evocation spells:</p>

<p>base number = X*(Evoc skill/Spell Level) + (research skill/10) + (specialization Evocation/10).</p>

<p>Where spell level is the level of the spell being cast. X is a modifier based on class. 2 for wizards, 1 for other classes (if crit hits are not wizard only).</p>


<p><b>Thanks for the well written suggestion. Critical hits on spells is something we have discussed in the past. I personally think it's an excellent idea, and that it could be balanced to account for the different power scales over our continents. That being said, we don't have the time to allocate adding this type of functionality right now. Critical spell hits would be a big change requiring a lot of play testing. currently there are no plans to add it, but I won't rule it out as a feature that we may decide to add at some point down the road.</p> 

<p>Thanks for the feedback, and glad you enjoy the game so much</p>

<p>- Lawrence Poe</b></p>

<p>View the rest of the thread <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000207.html" target="_blank">Here</a>.</p>

<p>Ezrick Blackpriest wrote:</p>

<p>I've brought this up as a bug with Esther twice with no response. I'll assume its not and then simply ask you: why?</p>

<p>When the wizard spell Evacuate is cast every mana user in the party is charged mana for the spell. As a 57th cleric with a 200 wisdom this spell costs me a full bubble of mana when cast by a wizard. As far as I know this is the only spell in the game that subtracts mana from every caster in the group when cast.</p>

<p>This is not the largest issue in the game certainly, but its, well, annoying. Because this spell is normally cast in an emergency when things are going badly the additional mana drain just adds to whatever frustration you already had over things going badly.</p>

<p>So is this a bug, or a 'feature'? If it is intended, why?</p>

<p><b>This *is* intentional. Evac is a group spell. One of its components is a mana drain. That component, just like the Evac, will hit every member of the group. This was added to stop people from Evacing to a relative safe area then have the MOBs come after them where they are near the zone line and can easily escape should things go bad.</p>

<p>Recently we have changed the interzone teleports to clear agro, so that feature of the spell is a little less important. We have talked about removing the mana drain but have yet to make a decision. Hopefully I can give you an answer sometime soon.</p>

<p>Hope that clears things up for ya.</p>

<p>- Lawrence Poe</b></p>


<p>Jaeden_Avengarious wrote:</p>

<p>For the Deity imbue spells, the level for them set is for 29. The only different one is Imbue Ivory, which is level 34.</p>

<p>Is there a special reason for this?</p>


<p><b>Yep, It should be set to the correct level of 29 in the next patch, thanks for the feedback.</p>

<p>- Lawrence Poe</b></p>


<p>View the rest of the thread <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000208.html" target="_blank">Here</a>.</p>

<p>A wondering Shadowknight wrote:</p>

<p>I realise this may have been intentional as part of the patch but I just wanted to express my concern as part of the SK community. Before the last patch Speed of Shissar, from the Enchanter Epic, simply overwrote spells such as Shadow Vortex and Shroud of Pain. Shadow Vortex and Shroud of Pain are minor AC drains which are very commonly used on raids and in normal grouping situations to manage aggro. This is especially true when preparing to break Mez on a mob.</p>

<p>Since the latest patch Speed of Shissar will not land on me if I've used Shroud of Pain or Shadow Vortex or Shroud of Hate. Unless, of course, Speed of Shissar is cast upon me beforehand, then I can use Shadow Vortex, etc, until Shissar wears off at which point Shissar either has to be refreshed while the icon is flashing or I have to wait until these self-only drain spells wear off, they cannot be clicked off.</p>

<p><b>The problem is how Speed of the Shissar is built in our spell database. This is the same problem that Call of Earth has. I'd like to be able to tell you "I'll move some stuff around and throw it up on test to see if it works" unfortunately I can't fix it right now. I've looked over the problems with speed of the Shissar a few dozen times. All I can really tell you is that a number of stacking complications we currently have should be rectified in the coming Months.</p> 

<p>- Lawrence Poe</b></p>


<p>A_Laker_Fan_01 wrote:</p>

<p>Hello, i had a question for Mr. Poe about the stacking of certain spells. In this case its 2 dots, the shaman epic dot and the enchanter debuff dot asphixiate.</p>
<p>At present time, if the shaman dot is on the mob first, then the chanter dot will stick, BUT if the chanter dot is on first then the shaman cant land his spell.</p>

<p>I know i might be possibly asking for a nerf (by exposing this problem) but, it seems to me that if it stacks one way, it should also stack the other way. Especially since the shaman dot is dmg only and the chanter one is a combination debuff and dmg dot.</p>

<p>Any clarification would be appreciated.</p>

<p>A_Laker_Fan_01</p>

<p>/secret handshake</p>

<p>Only 4 more!!!</p>


<p><b>The spells are not actually stacking in either order. They both share a DOT Hit point component in one of the effect slots. If Asphyxiate is on the MOB Curse of the Spirits will overwrite the effect. If Curse of the Spirits is on the MOB Asphyxiate, because the HP component is less, will fail to take hold. I hope this clear it up for you.</p>

<p>Looking like we're actually going to see a good series!</p> 
<br>GO LAKERS!

<p>- Lawrence Poe</b></p>


<p>You can access the rest of the thread <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000191.html" target="_blank">Here</a>.</p>

<p>Phew...ok, thats all the spell news for today. =)
<br>-Feltink Ithink</p>
</blockquote>


